canonical:
  title: 放洋遭大風舟回不行還泊于藍乙老浦
  author: 朴瑞生
  language: lzh
  text: 靡盬惟王事懸帆向日東風撞巨鼇窟舟盪老蛟宮人物扶搖裏形骸怳惚中艱危何足說頭上有蒼穹
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 放洋遭大風舟回不行還泊于藍乙老浦
  author: 朴瑞生
  language: lzh
  text: 靡盬惟王事。懸帆向日東。風撞巨鼇窟。舟盪老蛟宮。人物扶搖裏。形骸怳惚中。艱危何足說。頭上有蒼穹。
korean:
  title: 바다로 나가다가 큰 바람을 만나 배가 더 가지 못하고 돌아와 남을로포에 대다
  author: 박서생
  language: kor
  text: |-
    왕사가 쉴 새 없이
    돛폭을 올려 일본 동쪽 바람으로 향하네
    바람은 큰 굴을 두드리고
    배는 늙은 이무기 궁에서 뒤흔들리네
    사람들은 흔들림 속에서
    형해는 총황 중에 있어
    어렵고 위태로움을 족히 말할 게 있으랴
    머리 위에 푸른 하늘이 있네
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0130_010_0890&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: Setting Sail Eastward, Caught in a Great Storm, Unable to Proceed, Returning to Anchor at Namu Floating Wharf
  author: Park Seo-saeng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Ceaselessly bound by duty to the realm,
    I raise the sail toward the eastern wind of Japan.
    The gale strikes at the giant turtle's cavern,
    Our vessel tosses in the old dragon's palace.

    Amidst the rolling chaos, we are swept along—
    Our forms grow dim and wavering.
    What words could capture such peril and dread?
    Yet above our heads shines the vault of heaven.
  footnotes:
    - The 'giant turtle's cavern' and 'old dragon's palace' are poetic references to the depths of the sea, suggesting both the supernatural forces at work and the overwhelming power of nature.
    - The poem employs a progression from external chaos (wind and waves) to internal dissolution (dimming forms), before closing with a transcendent image of the eternal sky—a common device in East Asian poetry to assert spiritual steadfastness amid crisis.
